  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3abe573807997983",
      "text": "A familiar conversation from five different jobs. The backstory involves a monolith at a fast growing startup. Success! The business wildly outgrows the monolith. The drama builds as the costs of disentangling critical business process from the monolith are deferred and postponed. The monolith gets emotionally divested by everyone in the business but the costs continue to be deferred. Some people leave and crucial context is lost. Never seen how that story actually ends."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "01a8f6dab1f8e5a8",
      "text": "We took this question to former coworkers where there had been some success in both whittling services out of the monolith and also improving parts that remained within."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "6c3e94e9c9ecb692",
      "text": "> One thing that causes huge problems is that once the decision to break apart the monolith happens, everyone seems to forget that the monolith should be maintained and treated as a first class citizen of an SOA. It’s very hard to justify removing everything from a monolith and decommissioning it completely so rather than seeing it as a replacement effort it should be thought of as a rebalancing effort. The critical services that need more resources, different architecture, etc than the monolith are the good first choices for extraction."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
